Impact to our thesis
In-line Financial results versus consensus
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research
WPR upgraded 2025 EPS guidance by \(1\%\) to 16.64cps; the company delivered 1H25 EPS of 8.3c (MSE 8.2c).
The previous guidance had assumed no buy-backs (A\\$33m of shares been repurchased to date, of the A\\$50m program).
The debt book is well hedged with c.85% of interest rate exposure fixed at c.3%, through to 2027; so exposure to RBA rate cuts is likely to be small.
A\\$35m of assets are held for sale as at Jun- 25 (already contracted), at a passing yield of 7.7%. The bulk of these had settled in Jul/Aug- 25.
On growth potential, WPR has yet to receive any funding request by VEA on capital works contributions for OTR conversion projects.

WPR's 1H25 result delivered as per expectations for a triple-net lease REIT, and mgmt unlocked an EPS upgrade, which we think was enabled by the now- revised expectation that the A\\$50m buyback will be completed in 2H25. Gearing remains steady at 32.5%, providing flexibility (eg funding of OTR conversions); although disappointingly, it has yet to be offered the opportunity to participate in any growth capex by its major tenant, despite WPR's strategy of rolling out OTR set- ups across their sites.

The next 12 months will see WPR enter a new era - as its foundation portfolio - all tenanted by VEA, commences its lease expiry phase. When WPR was established in 2016, its leases ranged 10- 18yrs in duration - and 2026 will see c.4% of leases expiring (and subject to market rent review), followed by 6.7% in 2027. Reviews since IPO, predominantly for non- fuel tenants, have seen leasing spreads average - 4.4%.

WPR offg investors a good steady stream of income, with limited exposure to opex (other than overheads), and a stable cost of debt; on the flip side, it does not offer those seeking stronger growth that some REITs may offer as we emerge from the trough of the property cycle.
MORGAN STANLEY AUSTRALIA LIMITED+

Our PT is derived from a 10/50/40 weighting of our Bull/Base/Bear case scenarios. Each one is calculated using a combination of DCF and NAV.
Our DCF (Base case A\(2.72) is derived from an equity beta of 0.75, and Ke discount rate of 8.5\%. We also assume leasing spreads of - 5\% to account for lower petrol volumes.
Our NAV (Base case A\(2.98) assumes 25bps of cap rate compression.

- Interest rate decline 
- given WPR's bond-like returns- Uplift in tenant sales volumes and/or margins
- Increasing rates in Australia and globally- A faster and more rapid take-up of electric vehicles in Australia- Carbon policies

Equal- weight (E). The stock's total return is expected to be in line with the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk- adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.

Not- Rated (NR). Currently the analyst does not have adequate conviction about the stock's total return relative to the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk- adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.
